			<p>Most good things in life are coaxed, planned, nurtured, rather than merely snatched opportunities. (These add &#8217;spice&#8217;, I know, but without the staple foods, spice alone is rather unsatisfying.)<br />
Yes, sometimes we need to snap the shot and hope it came out ok, but that&#8217;s no excuse for putting little thought into most of what we do. Take a &#8216;classic&#8217; sunset, for example. Most are grab-it-while-you-can. But how much better it could be if you know the scene, think ahead where you&#8217;d stand (to avoid the lamp-post but get the tree silhouetted), know what time you need to be there, to look out for the sort of late afternoon sky that will give a good sunset&#8230; etc, etc.</p>

		</li>

	
	
		<li id="comment-61900">
			<img alt='' src='http://www.gravatar.com/avatar/e2f93eb0a633237f7014465cda094695?s=32&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.digital-photography-school.com%2Fwp-includes%2Fimages%2Fblank.gif&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-32 photo' height='32' width='32' />			<div class="comment-author"><cite>Ender</cite> Says:			
